{"query": {"pages": {"2037023": {"lastrevid": 555583589, "pageid": 2037023, "canonicalurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_action_(sociology)", "title": "Mass action (sociology)", "editurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&action=edit", "length": 2631, "contentmodel": "wikitext", "pagelanguage": "en", "touched": "2015-03-18T13:54:54Z", "ns": 0, "fullurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_action_(sociology)", "revisions": [{"*": "<div class=\"hatnote\">For other uses, see <a href=\"/wiki/Mass_action_(disambiguation)\" title=\"Mass action (disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Mass action (disambiguation)</a>.</div>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks ambox ambox-content ambox-Unreferenced\" role=\"presentation\"><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png\" width=\"50\" height=\"39\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"262\" data-file-height=\"204\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><span class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>does not <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citing sources\">cite</a> any <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability\" title=\"Wikipedia:Verifiability\">references or sources</a></b>.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> Please help <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&amp;action=edit\">improve this article</a> by <a href=\"/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing/1\" title=\"Help:Introduction to referencing/1\">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence\" title=\"Wikipedia:Verifiability\">removed</a>.</span>  <small><i>(December 2009)</i></small><span class=\"hide-when-compact\"></span></span></td></tr></table>\n<p><b>Mass action</b> in <a href=\"/wiki/Sociology\" title=\"Sociology\">sociology</a> refers to the situations where a large number of people behave simultaneously in a similar way but individually and without coordination.\n</p><p>For example, at any given moment, many thousands of people are shopping - without any coordination between themselves, they are nonetheless performing the same mass action. Another, more complicated example would be one based on a work of 19th century <a href=\"/wiki/Germany\" title=\"Germany\">German</a> sociologist <a href=\"/wiki/Max_Weber\" title=\"Max Weber\">Max Weber</a>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Protestant_Ethic_and_the_Spirit_of_Capitalism\" title=\"The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism\">The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism</a></i>: Weber wrote that <a href=\"/wiki/Capitalism\" title=\"Capitalism\">capitalism</a> evolved when the <a href=\"/wiki/Protestant\" title=\"Protestant\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Protestant</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Ethic\" title=\"Ethic\" class=\"mw-redirect\">ethic</a> influenced large number of people to create their own <a href=\"/wiki/Organization\" title=\"Organization\">enterprises</a> and engage in <a href=\"/wiki/Trade\" title=\"Trade\">trade</a> and gathering of <a href=\"/wiki/Wealth\" title=\"Wealth\">wealth</a>. In other words, the Protestant ethic was a force behind an unplanned and uncoordinated mass action that led to the development of capitalism.\n</p><p>A <a href=\"/wiki/Bank_run\" title=\"Bank run\">bank run</a> is mass action with sweeping implications. Upon hearing news of a bank's anticipated insolvency, hundreds or thousands of bank depositors simultaneously rush down to a bank branch to withdraw their deposits, and protect their savings.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2008)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p><p>More developed forms of mass actions are <a href=\"/wiki/Group_behavior\" title=\"Group behavior\" class=\"mw-redirect\">group behavior</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Group_action_(sociology)\" title=\"Group action (sociology)\">group action</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><div id=\"toctitle\"><h2>Contents</h2></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Epidemiology_meaning\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Epidemiology meaning</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Popular_Culture\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Popular Culture</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Footnotes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Footnotes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Epidemiology_meaning\">Epidemiology meaning</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Epidemiology meaning\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In epidemiological (disease) models, assuming the \"law of mass action\" means assuming that individuals are homogeneously mixed and every individual is about as likely to interact with every other individual. This is a common assumption in models such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Compartmental_models_in_epidemiology\" title=\"Compartmental models in epidemiology\">SIR model</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Popular_Culture\">Popular Culture</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Popular Culture\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>This idea serves as the main plot theme in author <a href=\"/wiki/Isaac_Asimov\" title=\"Isaac Asimov\">Isaac Asimov</a>'s work, <a href=\"/wiki/Foundation_series\" title=\"Foundation series\">Foundation</a>. The main character, <a href=\"/wiki/Hari_Seldon\" title=\"Hari Seldon\">Hari Seldon</a>, uses mass action to foresee the imminent fall of the Galactic Empire, which encompasses the entire Milky Way, and a dark age lasting thirty thousand years before a second great empire arises. With this, he hopes to reduce that dark age to only one thousand years by creating an Encyclopedia to retain all current knowledge.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Social_action\" title=\"Social action\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Social action</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Collective_behavior\" title=\"Collective behavior\">Collective behavior</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Collective_effervescence\" title=\"Collective effervescence\">Collective effervescence</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Footnotes\">Footnotes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Footnotes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n</div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li> Louis C. Fraina, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://archive.org/details/MassActionAndIndustrialUnionism\">\"Mass Action and Industrial Unionism,\"</a> <i>International Socialist Review,</i> vol. 17, no. 9 (March 1917), pp. 556-557.</li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Vista_Login_Manager_Cropped.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Vista_Login_Manager_Cropped.svg/40px-Vista_Login_Manager_Cropped.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Vista_Login_Manager_Cropped.svg/60px-Vista_Login_Manager_Cropped.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Vista_Login_Manager_Cropped.svg/80px-Vista_Login_Manager_Cropped.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"100\" data-file-height=\"76\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Sociology\" title=\"Sociology\">sociology</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Mass_action_(sociology)&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Socio-stub\" title=\"Te